**After fix (fix/sanitize-error-context-96007)** — The classified error label is followed by all safe follow-up prose: patrol results, recommendation, and next steps are preserved and visible to the user.

![96007_after-fix](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7c29e085-df90-427e-8add-f5ce1f9d32fb)

### Trigger chain (round 4)

```
mock-server.py (HTTP 200 + finish_reason: "interrupted")
  → openai-stop-reason.ts catch-all → stopReason: "error"
  → finalizeAssistantExtraction() → errorContext: true
  → sanitizeUserFacingText(text, { errorContext: true })
  → ERROR_PREFIX_RE matches leading "Error: connection timed out..."
  → classifyErrorPrefixLine(leadingLine) → "LLM request timed out."
  → suffix passes isUnsafeMultilineErrorBody check
  → result: "LLM request timed out.\n\nRecommendation: ...\nNext steps:\n..."
```

## Root Cause

In `sanitizeUserFacingText`, when `errorContext` is `true` and the trimmed text matches `ERROR_PREFIX_RE`, the function unconditionally rewrote the entire payload into a short templated error label. It did not check whether the text contains substantive multi-line prose after the error prefix that should be preserved, nor did it guard against raw stack frames and error payload bodies leaking through.

Four missing cases in the error-suffix guard:
1. `STACK_FRAME_LINE_RE` used `[^():]+` for the path portion, excluding colon characters — missing `node:internal/...`, `file:///...`, and Windows `C:\...` stack frames
2. `suffix.trim()` stripped leading whitespace from the first stack-frame line, so `^\s+at\s+` failed to match it — 2-frame stacks with a trimmed first line fell below the detection threshold
3. The regex did not match async V8 frames (`at async … (path:line:col)`) — `async` between `at` and the function name caused the optional function-name group to consume `async` as a function name, leaving the path unmatched
4. Security-sensitive diagnostic lines (auth headers, API endpoint URLs, request/correlation/trace IDs) were not detected — `isUnsafeMultilineErrorBody` only checked for stack frames, JSON bodies, and HTML pages

## User-visible / Behavior Changes

Channel replies that contain an error-prefix line followed by user-visible prose (e.g. recommendations, next steps) will now show the prose content after the error prefix, rather than being replaced entirely by a short error label. Raw stack frames (including colon-bearing Node/V8 paths), JSON error bodies, and HTML error pages are stripped from the suffix.

